I can remember thinking to myself,

82
00:02:55,189 --> 00:02:55,469
you know,

83
00:02:55,590 --> 00:02:57,310
he's definitely got more aggression than me,

84
00:02:57,409 --> 00:02:58,830
and you just, you know, you did.

85
00:02:58,930 --> 00:03:00,150
You had a lot more aggression than me.

86
00:03:00,210 --> 00:03:01,550
It's a work in progress still, mate.

87
00:03:02,849 --> 00:03:04,710
But yeah, I was a bit surprised,

88
00:03:04,770 --> 00:03:07,349
because I didn't realise growing up down South,

89
00:03:07,449 --> 00:03:10,810
the rivalry between Ross Trevor and Sacred Heart.

90
00:03:10,909 --> 00:03:11,530
And I was wondering,

91
00:03:11,689 --> 00:03:13,250
why is this guy so fired up?

92
00:03:13,310 --> 00:03:14,930
And I just had to try and settle you down.

93
00:03:15,030 --> 00:03:17,650
But I just love playing footy with you.

94
00:03:17,650 --> 00:03:18,810
And I remember, you know,

95
00:03:19,629 --> 00:03:21,150
I just had this sense you're going to be a good player.

96
00:03:21,409 --> 00:03:23,030
And you hadn't put it all together.

97
00:03:23,150 --> 00:03:24,370
You were still growing at that stage.

98
00:03:24,449 --> 00:03:26,849
But I remember really making sure when I had the ball,

99
00:03:26,930 --> 00:03:28,330
I'd kick it to you as much as I could

100
00:03:28,330 --> 00:03:30,729
and trying to support you as much as I could.

101
00:03:30,810 --> 00:03:32,449
And then it was just awesome for me to,

102
00:03:33,090 --> 00:03:34,849
you know, when my journey ended with footy,

103
00:03:34,930 --> 00:03:37,349
to be able to watch you continuously get better and better

104
00:03:37,349 --> 00:03:38,430
and watch from afar.

105
00:03:38,629 --> 00:03:39,810
And no, it was brilliant, mate.

106
00:03:39,849 --> 00:03:41,250
We loved having you on board.

107
00:03:41,389 --> 00:03:43,050
And yeah, been great mates ever since.

108
00:03:43,210 --> 00:03:45,050
Yeah, it was a fierce school rivalry

109
00:03:45,050 --> 00:03:47,189
and a great friendship, mate,

110
00:03:47,189 --> 00:03:49,550
being able to come down and play,

111
00:03:49,629 --> 00:03:50,770
with you and we played all the way through.

112
00:03:50,870 --> 00:03:51,629
We ended up, you know,

113
00:03:51,650 --> 00:03:53,530
playing our first games in league football

114
00:03:53,530 --> 00:03:54,930
in South Australia with South Adelaide,

115
00:03:54,990 --> 00:03:57,110
I think a couple of weeks apart from memory.

116
00:03:57,250 --> 00:03:58,629
And it culminated in 1992.

117
00:03:58,629 --> 00:04:00,189
You were drafted to the Bombers.

118
00:04:00,669 --> 00:04:03,449
I was drafted under the father-son to the Bulldogs,

119
00:04:03,550 --> 00:04:05,969
which was probably the fulfillment of a lifelong dream.

120
00:04:06,069 --> 00:04:07,490
But unfortunately for you, mate,

121
00:04:07,550 --> 00:04:09,349
now last game of South Adelaide,

122
00:04:09,409 --> 00:04:11,090
you shattered your ankle horrifically

123
00:04:11,090 --> 00:04:13,729
to the point where the Bombers thought

124
00:04:13,729 --> 00:04:16,709
that it was a two-year recovery and didn't take you over.

125
00:04:16,889 --> 00:04:18,329
But how hard was that on you?

126
00:04:18,569 --> 00:04:19,610
Because it changed your life.

127
00:04:19,610 --> 00:04:20,509
Pretty much from then.

128
00:04:20,990 --> 00:04:22,089
Yeah, it was at the time.

129
00:04:22,209 --> 00:04:25,029
I remember it's funny now because you feel so long ago

130
00:04:25,029 --> 00:04:27,730
that you feel like it's a different lifetime.

131
00:04:27,730 --> 00:04:30,110
But I do remember at the time really affecting me.

132
00:04:30,209 --> 00:04:32,230
I remember being, you know, very flat

133
00:04:32,230 --> 00:04:35,870
because, you know, for probably the five years

134
00:04:35,870 --> 00:04:37,529
leading up to it, you felt like, you know,

135
00:04:37,610 --> 00:04:38,910
potentially this could be my career.

136
00:04:38,990 --> 00:04:39,769
This could be my life.

137
00:04:40,230 --> 00:04:44,089
And it was those days where SADFL players

138
00:04:44,089 --> 00:04:45,709
and I'm sure Waffle players were the same

139
00:04:45,709 --> 00:04:47,569
is that you would go over and train

140
00:04:47,569 --> 00:04:49,250
with the team that drafted you.

141
00:04:49,250 --> 00:04:49,310
Yeah.

142
00:04:49,610 --> 00:04:51,069
I remember getting drafted the first year

143
00:04:51,069 --> 00:04:53,769
and actually staying home, which is unheard of now.

144
00:04:53,850 --> 00:04:55,029
But a lot of us did do that.

145
00:04:55,149 --> 00:04:56,649
And including yourself, I think, Darce.

146
00:04:56,730 --> 00:04:59,029
But a lot of us stayed home that first year.

147
00:04:59,170 --> 00:05:02,410
And, you know, I always had in my mind that I'd go.

148
00:05:02,410 --> 00:05:05,110
But the experience of training at an AFL club

149
00:05:05,110 --> 00:05:08,269
over that pre-season, really just amazing.

150
00:05:08,430 --> 00:05:09,730
And you just think, you know, this is going to happen.

151
00:05:09,850 --> 00:05:10,569
This is going to be great.

152
00:05:10,670 --> 00:05:13,089
So you almost get a taste of it and then it's taken away.

153
00:05:13,250 --> 00:05:15,709
So I do remember dwelling on it for a few months.

154
00:05:15,829 --> 00:05:18,910
But it's probably with me not so much in my nature

155
00:05:18,910 --> 00:05:21,009
to continue to dwell on that.

156
00:05:21,129 --> 00:05:23,470
I recognise that, you know, that door is closed for me.

157
00:05:23,930 --> 00:05:25,649
Gave it a little bit of a go to come back,

158
00:05:25,730 --> 00:05:26,949
but it didn't quite work out.

159
00:05:27,170 --> 00:05:29,189
I remember you coming back from your first training session

160
00:05:29,189 --> 00:05:29,709
at the Bombers.

161
00:05:29,790 --> 00:05:31,990
We were desperate to make it in the AFL

162
00:05:31,990 --> 00:05:34,529
and you'd done a weight session with the great Paul Salmon

163
00:05:34,529 --> 00:05:37,889
and you were full of life and full of stories, as you said.

164
00:05:38,610 --> 00:05:40,870
And you were, mate, I've said this very often,

165
00:05:41,170 --> 00:05:43,870
a star player and athletically gifted.

166
00:05:44,529 --> 00:05:47,069
Unfortunately, that recovery meant that that chapter was closed.

167
00:05:47,170 --> 00:05:48,170
But I often tell this story.

168
00:05:48,170 --> 00:05:48,829
You went to teachers.

169
00:05:48,910 --> 00:05:51,269
You went to college, which is where our paths crossed again

170
00:05:51,269 --> 00:05:54,209
and became a legendary teacher in South Australia.

171
00:05:54,949 --> 00:05:58,110
And I remember, you know, we stayed in touch

172
00:05:58,110 --> 00:06:00,569
and you're a great friend connecting all the way through

173
00:06:00,569 --> 00:06:01,610
whenever you came to Melbourne.

174
00:06:02,050 --> 00:06:05,069
But I'd occasionally hear the stories of a friend of a friend

175
00:06:05,069 --> 00:06:08,089
or someone I knew ended up in Matt Waterwitz's class

176
00:06:08,089 --> 00:06:11,810
and that it was a life-changing experience to be in your classroom.

177
00:06:12,149 --> 00:06:16,850
And I know you're probably humble enough not to want to go too far into that,

178
00:06:16,850 --> 00:06:18,850
but you clearly had a passion for being a teacher.

179
00:06:18,910 --> 00:06:20,629
And you were clearly really good at it.

180
00:06:21,350 --> 00:06:22,189
Yeah, it's funny.

181
00:06:22,329 --> 00:06:24,490
I think when you reflect on it,

182
00:06:24,509 --> 00:06:27,389
I reckon the original idea for getting into teaching

183
00:06:27,389 --> 00:06:29,089
was the idea that I could do PE

184
00:06:29,089 --> 00:06:31,449
and that I could have 12 weeks a year holiday.

185
00:06:31,629 --> 00:06:33,850
So I think if I search really honestly in myself,

186
00:06:33,930 --> 00:06:34,569
that was the reason.

187
00:06:34,709 --> 00:06:36,470
But I remember in my last year,

188
00:06:36,629 --> 00:06:39,110
and I still, you know, probably not dismissing the fact

189
00:06:39,110 --> 00:06:41,110
that I really love working with kids.

190
00:06:41,269 --> 00:06:44,370
But in my last year, I remember doing this presentation.

191
00:06:44,509 --> 00:06:46,449
It was my final presentation at university

192
00:06:46,449 --> 00:06:48,129
and it was about accountability.

193
00:06:48,230 --> 00:06:48,889
And, you know,

194
00:06:49,029 --> 00:06:50,689
you're going out in the world to become a teacher.

195
00:06:51,689 --> 00:06:54,069
What's the most important things in terms of accountability?

196
00:06:54,310 --> 00:06:56,410
And there's so many things you're accountable for.

197
00:06:56,509 --> 00:06:59,050
You know, you're accountable for the students in your care.

198
00:06:59,170 --> 00:07:01,589
You're accountable for the teachers around you,

199
00:07:01,589 --> 00:07:02,629
the school values.

200
00:07:02,750 --> 00:07:04,529
You're accountable to the Department of Education.

201
00:07:04,689 --> 00:07:05,069
You're accountable.

202
00:07:05,670 --> 00:07:06,329
And I remember this.

203
00:07:06,750 --> 00:07:08,930
I remember thinking, I've nailed this presentation.

204
00:07:09,129 --> 00:07:09,829
Like, this is great.

205
00:07:09,910 --> 00:07:12,230
I'm going to get some great responses here.

206
00:07:12,509 --> 00:07:14,589
I'll get a good score and away we go.

207
00:07:14,649 --> 00:07:15,050
I finished.

208
00:07:15,490 --> 00:07:17,370
And luckily for me,

209
00:07:17,470 --> 00:07:18,709
or luckily for me in that,

210
00:07:18,709 --> 00:07:21,089
my lecturer at the time was away.

211
00:07:22,009 --> 00:07:25,550
And a philosophy major PhD doctor came in

212
00:07:25,550 --> 00:07:27,970
and he was looking after our class that day.

213
00:07:28,250 --> 00:07:30,149
And I'd finished my presentation sitting down,

214
00:07:30,290 --> 00:07:31,230
feeling good about myself.

215
00:07:31,689 --> 00:07:34,269
And he said, Matt, I've got a concern for you here.

216
00:07:34,329 --> 00:07:37,990
And he said, I think if I was a teacher sitting in this room right now,

217
00:07:37,990 --> 00:07:40,829
I'd be thinking, why the hell am I going to be a teacher?

218
00:07:40,990 --> 00:07:43,410
Because you've just told me about all these terrible things

219
00:07:43,410 --> 00:07:45,350
that I now need to worry about.

220
00:07:45,970 --> 00:07:47,689
So think about the list now, Matt.

221
00:07:47,689 --> 00:07:48,449
And you tell me,

222
00:07:48,449 --> 00:07:51,269
what is the most important thing you're accountable for as a teacher?

223
00:07:51,930 --> 00:07:54,509
And of course, there's a long silence and a big pause by me.

224
00:07:54,569 --> 00:07:55,649
And I'm thinking through the list

225
00:07:55,649 --> 00:07:57,870
and I'm thinking about all this stuff that I've just covered,

226
00:07:58,610 --> 00:07:59,329
wondering what is it?

227
00:07:59,350 --> 00:08:01,290
And of course, you know, you come straight back to it.

228
00:08:01,350 --> 00:08:03,930
It is actually, you're accountable to the kids in your care.

229
00:08:04,550 --> 00:08:07,750
And so that was big for me because I just thought, right,

230
00:08:08,029 --> 00:08:10,949
if that's true, then I've got to get bloody good at this job.

231
00:08:11,149 --> 00:08:14,050
So I can't really just think about the 12 weeks of your holidays

232
00:08:14,050 --> 00:08:16,649
and kicking the footy with the kids out in the oval,

233
00:08:16,649 --> 00:08:18,389
which is my original intention.

234
00:08:18,889 --> 00:08:20,589
I've actually got to really take this seriously.

235
00:08:20,910 --> 00:08:24,009
And that way you really enjoy it because it's part of your value.

236
00:08:24,310 --> 00:08:26,350
So that's how I got into that.

237
00:08:26,769 --> 00:08:29,410
There's around 25 kids, I understand,

238
00:08:29,629 --> 00:08:32,470
were troubled and having challenges at school.

239
00:08:32,549 --> 00:08:35,850
And schools traditionally manage kids out of school

240
00:08:35,850 --> 00:08:37,990
who maybe aren't living up to the standard.

241
00:08:38,190 --> 00:08:41,769
You're at a Cardone College on the McLaren Vale of South Australia

242
00:08:41,769 --> 00:08:46,330
and some of those kids are probably going to get exited out of the school in year 10.

243
00:08:46,330 --> 00:08:47,610
And you go to the principal and you say,

244
00:08:47,690 --> 00:08:49,889
I became a teacher for these kids.

245
00:08:49,990 --> 00:08:51,029
Give me these kids.

246
00:08:51,409 --> 00:08:52,490
But there was a couple of conditions.

247
00:08:52,649 --> 00:08:54,429
Can you pick up the story and tell us what happened?

248
00:08:54,809 --> 00:08:55,090
Yeah.

249
00:08:55,549 --> 00:08:58,590
Originally, I was a bit challenged by it because I just had this belief

250
00:08:58,590 --> 00:09:01,490
that every classroom teacher should be integrating

251
00:09:02,049 --> 00:09:04,129
and finding opportunities for those kids.

252
00:09:04,470 --> 00:09:08,889
And I was sort of diametrically opposed to getting them out of class at the start.

253
00:09:08,990 --> 00:09:12,590
But when I really realised that they were going to be turfed out,

254
00:09:13,129 --> 00:09:14,990
I just came up with some alternatives.

255
00:09:14,990 --> 00:09:17,309
And I got together with a great mate of mine,

256
00:09:17,309 --> 00:09:19,149
who's now working with us, DAS, Damien Hill.

257
00:09:19,610 --> 00:09:22,350
And we came up with this concept of masterclass,

258
00:09:22,490 --> 00:09:26,190
which is this fully integrated rich task scenario

259
00:09:26,190 --> 00:09:30,269
where the kids would be immersed in deep learning for each term of the year.

260
00:09:30,929 --> 00:09:35,470
And the way that we tapped into the interest of the kids is,

